\description{
Drives an Iterative Ensemble Smoother entirely in R, using a user-supplied
forward model callable instead of the PEST++ \code{.pst}-file invocation cycle.
Each iteration:
}
\details{
\enumerate{
\item Evaluates \code{forward_model(par_ensemble)} to obtain simulated observations.
\item Forms parameter / observation anomalies and residuals.
\item Calls the C++ kernel \code{\link[=ensemble_solution]{ensemble_solution()}} (GLM form, Chen & Oliver 2013)
to compute an \verb{nreal x npar} upgrade.
\item Adds the upgrade to the current ensemble.
}

The classic \code{.pst}-file path remains available via \code{\link[=pesto_ies]{pesto_ies()}} for full
PEST++ compatibility. Use this callback driver when the forward model is
itself an R function (e.g. an \code{apsimx} wrapper from \code{\link[=apsim_callback]{apsim_callback()}},
a Python bridge, or a synthetic test problem) and the per-realisation
file-I/O overhead of the \code{.pst} path is the bottleneck.

Phase-1 behaviour: single lambda per iteration (or a user-supplied schedule).
A line-search over \code{ies_lambda_mults} matching \code{pestpp-ies} is a planned
Phase-2 enhancement; for the common case of a well-behaved forward model
with \code{lambda = 1}, the GLM update reduces phi reliably (see vignette
\code{apsim-callback}).
}
\section{Multi-fidelity}{

When \code{forward_model} is a \code{\link[=pesto_multifidelity_model]{pesto_multifidelity_model()}}, \code{fidelity_schedule}
